WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.720
Hey Rockstar, do you know if your R and Python packages are out for delivery?

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:08.400
Let me show you how to know.

00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:11.080
Head over to RStudio Package Manager.

00:00:11.080 --> 00:00:14.800
You'll probably land on the top repo your system administrator has set up for you.

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:18.760
In the top navigation bar, head over to Setup.

00:00:18.760 --> 00:00:23.360
Scroll down below the calendar, click on the Change link.

00:00:23.360 --> 00:00:26.820
Select the operating system that your IDE is running on.

00:00:26.820 --> 00:00:29.500
In my case that's Ubuntu 20.04.

00:00:29.500 --> 00:00:31.280
Select OK.

00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:32.700
Select the Binary button.

00:00:32.700 --> 00:00:37.439
This ensures you'll be installing precompiled binary versions of the packages, saving you

00:00:37.439 --> 00:00:39.680
hours of time.

00:00:39.680 --> 00:00:44.759
Click the Copy button to copy this unique URL to your clipboard.

00:00:44.759 --> 00:00:48.799
Then head back over to your RStudio IDE.

00:00:48.799 --> 00:00:53.139
In the Tools menu at the top, go down to Global Options.

00:00:53.139 --> 00:00:56.880
In the left sidebar, click on Packages.

00:00:56.880 --> 00:00:59.400
And then the Change button.

00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:03.500
And then paste in the URL that you copied from Package Manager.

00:01:03.500 --> 00:01:05.540
Click OK and OK.

00:01:05.540 --> 00:01:06.620
That's it.

00:01:06.620 --> 00:01:11.739
That's the simplest way to connect RStudio Package Manager to your RStudio IDE.

00:01:11.739 --> 00:01:13.540
It can be a lot more complicated than that.

00:01:13.540 --> 00:01:16.139
There's multiple ways to do this, but this is your first step.

00:01:16.139 --> 00:01:17.139
Give it a shot.

00:01:17.139 --> 00:01:17.980
Bring those packages home.

